{{about|real estate|the game|Finca (game)|the nonprofit corporation|FINCA International}}
[[File:Finca.jpg|thumb|Finca]]
[[File:Finca 02.jpg|thumb|A finca in Mallorca]]
[[File:Finca-CanFrareVerd-Ibiza.JPG|thumb|Finca ''Can Frare Verd'', Ibiza]]
In English usage, a '''finca''' ({{IPA-es|ˈfiŋka|}}; {{langnf||Spanish|an "estate"}})<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/english/finca | title=Finca|work=Oxford Dictionaries|accessdate= November 9, 2015}}</ref> refers to a piece of rural or agricultural land, typically with a [[cottage]], [[farmhouse]] or [[estate (land)|estate buildings]] present, and often adjacent to a woodland or plantation.

==Overview==
Especially in tourism, the term has recently gained the colloquial meaning of a holiday home in a rural setting, situated on the [[Peninsular Spain|Spanish mainland]], the [[Balearics]], and the [[Canary Islands]], and throughout the countries of Spanish-speaking [[Latin America]]. Similar rural properties can be found in [[Italy]], despite having a different name.{{what|date=January 2016}} 

Fincas can typically look back on an extensive development history, and are often older than 300 years. In some regions, however, especially on the Balearics, new buildings are erected.{{what|date=January 2016}}

